Her work with nanotechnology has helped to study more effective anti-malarial medicines, and through the World Bank, she's helped to secure millions of Dollars to fund African researchers. "I'm using nanotechnology, which is my training and expertise, to improve the availability of existing herbal extracts which are very potent but are lacking for example solubility," she says. Professor Swai earned the prestigious award together with a cash prize of $20 000. She tells Focus on Africa's Esau Williams about what motivated her in taking up a career in science and how she hopes to inspire other women in the field. "Science is not that difficult, itâ€™s just a myth, women are as good as men," she says. --BBC--